66
00:04:31,408 --> 00:04:37,828
Instead of treating pipelines like fragile
one-off scripts, we start treating them

67
00:04:37,888 --> 00:04:40,448
like version testable production assets.

68
00:04:41,048 --> 00:04:44,378
In other words, before
asking, " How good is a model?"

69
00:04:44,678 --> 00:04:49,738
We should probably ask, "How
trustworthy is a system that we feed

70
00:04:49,758 --> 00:04:54,578
the model into?" I break database
DevOps for AI into three pillars.

71
00:04:54,898 --> 00:05:00,238
The first is continuous integration for
data, which means automated validation,

72
00:05:00,348 --> 00:05:05,878
schema contract testing, and data quality
gates built into every pipeline change.

73
00:05:06,598 --> 00:05:09,498
The second is schema evolution management.

74
00:05:09,558 --> 00:05:14,758
Enterprise data changes constantly, and if
your downstream features or applications

75
00:05:14,798 --> 00:05:20,178
cannot adapt safely, then every schema
update becomes a mini heart attack.

76
00:05:20,908 --> 00:05:25,418
Version backward compatibility
schema management reduces that risk.

77
00:05:26,038 --> 00:05:28,738
The third pillar is
pipeline observability.

78
00:05:28,798 --> 00:05:33,658
You want end-to-end lineage,
SLA monitoring, and alerting

79
00:05:33,718 --> 00:05:36,178
across every transformation step.

80
00:05:36,878 --> 00:05:40,418
If the system is important
enough to drive decision, it is

81
00:05:40,458 --> 00:05:42,438
important enough to watch closely.

82
00:05:43,278 --> 00:05:46,408
Next, let's move into the
resilient cloud native pipe.

83
00:05:46,678 --> 00:05:51,958
A production pipeline should not
behave like a mystery novel where

84
00:05:52,018 --> 00:05:54,198
the ending surprises everyone.

85
00:05:54,258 --> 00:05:58,258
It should probably be a very
modular, testable, and boring

86
00:05:58,318 --> 00:05:59,918
in the best possible way.

87
00:06:00,738 --> 00:06:06,688
This deck highlights key principles
here: idempotency, modularity, fault

88
00:06:06,798 --> 00:06:12,118
tolerance, and versioned data sets
Idempotency means you can rerun safely.

89
00:06:12,898 --> 00:06:16,698
Modularity means each stage
can be deployed and tested

90
00:06:16,778 --> 00:06:18,298
independently of each other.

91
00:06:19,038 --> 00:06:24,528
Fault tolerance means one bad event
does not bring the whole system down.

92
00:06:25,078 --> 00:06:31,238
And versioned databases or datasets give
you reproducibility when someone asks,

93
00:06:32,038 --> 00:06:35,778
"Why did the model behave differently
last Tuesday?" When someone asks

94
00:06:35,798 --> 00:06:39,798
that question, we should be able to
answer that by getting the previous

95
00:06:39,858 --> 00:06:43,708
version, comparing, and then testing
and pre-- giving them the right answer.

96
00:06:44,238 --> 00:06:47,868
That question always comes on a Tuesday,
by the way, if you're wondering.

97
00:06:48,368 --> 00:06:50,808
Now, this is where MLOps enters.

98
00:06:51,788 --> 00:06:55,828
MLOps closes the loop between
experimentation and production by

99
00:06:55,848 --> 00:07:00,908
treating models as deployable engineering
assets rather than research artifacts.

100
00:07:01,308 --> 00:07:05,757
The presentation calls out model
versioning, automated CI/CD, and

101
00:07:05,757 --> 00:07:07,808
