equally to data as well as the models.

136
00:09:35,188 --> 00:09:41,478
Governance here includes data quality
gates, end-to-end lineage, access

137
00:09:41,538 --> 00:09:45,938
and compliance controls, and unified
models and data observability.

138
00:09:46,438 --> 00:09:51,918
In practical terms, that means
validating schemas, checking nulls

139
00:09:51,958 --> 00:09:57,698
and drifts, tracking the data from
raw sources to prediction, masking

140
00:09:57,798 --> 00:10:03,558
PII correctly, and monitoring not just
latency, but also the business impact.

141
00:10:04,078 --> 00:10:08,598
Governance should not be bolted on
after AI system is already live.

142
00:10:09,118 --> 00:10:11,458
At that point, governance
becomes archeology.

143
00:10:12,438 --> 00:10:17,298
It is much better to build it into
the architecture from day one.

144
00:10:17,798 --> 00:10:23,459
Observability across the stack This slide
is especially important because AI systems

145
00:10:23,539 --> 00:10:25,459
really fail with a dramatic explosion.

146
00:10:25,799 --> 00:10:27,738
More often, they fail very quietly.

147
00:10:27,959 --> 00:10:32,499
A feature could go stale, a
distribution shifts, latency could

148
00:10:32,579 --> 00:10:37,218
creep in, accuracy slips, and then
the business trust could erode.

149
00:10:37,677 --> 00:10:42,437
This deck breaks observability into data
layer, feature layer, and model layer.

150
00:10:42,897 --> 00:10:49,227
At the data layer, you monitor pipeline
SLAs, schema drifts And quality scores.

151
00:10:49,597 --> 00:10:52,437
At the feature layer, you
watch distribution shifts,

152
00:10:52,857 --> 00:10:54,887
freshness, and missing values.

153
00:10:55,277 --> 00:10:59,117
At the model layer, you look
at drift, latency, accuracy,

154
00:10:59,617 --> 00:11:01,697
and downstream business KPIs.

155
00:11:02,497 --> 00:11:04,677
Silent failure is the enemy here.

156
00:11:04,917 --> 00:11:09,497
A visible outage is painful, but a
wrong answer delivered confidently

157
00:11:09,637 --> 00:11:12,197
at scale is usually worse.

158
00:11:12,637 --> 00:11:17,317
Think about banking, think about
safety for an automated driving car.

159
00:11:18,137 --> 00:11:21,797
So those are the examples that you
need to think about when you're

160
00:11:21,857 --> 00:11:23,437
thinking about silent failure.

161
00:11:23,737 --> 00:11:29,597
Next, let's shift from batch intelligence
to real-time decision platforms.

162
00:11:30,097 --> 00:11:35,517
The point here is that modern decision
systems increasingly need sub-second

163
00:11:35,557 --> 00:11:41,517
inference, event-driven feature
computation, and seamless integration with

164
00:11:41,657 --> 00:11:44,317
